# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: remix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:remix/introduction] Everything in Remix starts with the compiler: `remix vite:build`.
[src:remix/introduction] A browser build, usually in `build/client/*`.
[src:remix/introduction] This includes automatic code splitting by route, fingerprinted asset imports (like CSS and images), etc.
[src:remix/introduction] Anything needed to run an application in the browser.
[src:remix/introduction] Both the client and the server use this manifest to know the entire dependency graph.
[src:remix/introduction] This is useful for preloading resources in the initial server render as well as prefetching them for client-side transitions.
[src:remix/introduction] This is how Remix is able to eliminate the render+fetch waterfalls so common in web apps today.
[src:remix/introduction] With these build artifacts, an application can be deployed to any hosting service that runs JavaScript.
[src:remix/introduction] While Remix runs on the server, it is not actually a server.
[src:remix/introduction] It's just a handler that is given to an actual JavaScript server.
[src:remix/introduction] It's built on the Web Fetch API instead of Node.js.
[src:remix/introduction] This enables Remix to run in any Node.js server like Vercel, Netlify, Architect, etc. as well as non-Node.js environments like Cloudflare Workers and Deno Deploy.
[src:remix/introduction] Express (or Node.js) is the actual server, Remix is just a handler on that server.
[src:remix/introduction] The `"@remix-run/express"` package is called an adapter.
[src:remix/introduction] Adapters make them work for a specific server by converting the server's request/response API into the Fetch API on the way in and then adapting the Fetch Response coming from Remix into the server's response API.
[src:remix/introduction] Real adapters do a bit more than that, but that's the gist of it.
[src:remix/introduction] Not only does this enable you to deploy Remix anywhere, it also lets you incrementally adopt it in an existing JavaScript server since you can have routes outside of Remix that your server continues to handle before getting to Remix.
[src:remix/introduction] Additionally, if Remix doesn't have an adapter for your server already, you can look at the source of one of the adapters and build your own.
[src:remix/introduction] If you're familiar with server-side MVC web frameworks like Rails and Laravel, Remix is the View and Controller, but it leaves the Model up to you.
[src:remix/introduction] There are a lot of great databases, ORMs, mailers, etc. in the JavaScript ecosystem to fill that space.
[src:remix/introduction] Remix also has helpers around the Fetch API for cookie and session management.
[src:remix/introduction] Instead of having a split between View and Controller, Remix Route modules take on both responsibilities.
[src:remix/introduction] Most server-side frameworks are "model focused".
[src:remix/introduction] A controller manages *multiple URLs* for a single model.
[src:remix/introduction] Routes can handle an entire URL or just a segment of the URL.
[src:remix/introduction] When a route maps to just a segment, the nested URL segments become nested layouts in the UI.
[src:remix/introduction] In this way, each layout (view) can be its own controller and then Remix will aggregate the data and components to build the complete UI.
[src:remix/introduction] More often than not, a Remix route module can contain both the UI and the interactions with the models in the same file, which leads to really nice developer ergonomics and productivity.
[src:remix/introduction] Route modules have three primary exports: `loader`, `action`, and `default` (component).
[src:remix/introduction] You can actually use Remix as just a server-side framework without using any browser JavaScript at all.
[src:remix/introduction] The route conventions for data loading with `loader`, mutations with `action` and HTML forms, and components that render at URLs, can provide the core feature set of a lot of web projects.
[src:remix/introduction] Not every page in your application needs a bunch of JavaScript in the browser, and not every user interaction requires any extra flair than the browser's default behaviors.
[src:remix/introduction] In Remix, you can build it the simple way first, and then scale up without changing the fundamental model.
[src:remix/introduction] Additionally, the majority of the app works before JavaScript loads in the browser, which makes Remix apps resilient to choppy network conditions by design.
[src:remix/introduction] If you're not familiar with traditional back-end web frameworks, you can think of Remix routes as React components that are already their own API route and already know how to load and submit data to themselves on the server.
[src:remix/introduction] Once Remix has served the document to the browser, it "hydrates" the page with the browser build's JavaScript modules.
[src:remix/introduction] This is where we talk a lot about Remix "emulating the browser".
[src:remix/introduction] When the user clicks a link, instead of making a round trip to the server for the entire document and all the assets, Remix simply fetches the data for the next page and updates the UI.
[src:remix/introduction] Additionally, when users submit a `<Form>` to update data, instead of doing a normal HTML document request, the browser runtime will make a fetch to the server instead and automatically revalidate all data on the page and update it with React.
[src:remix/introduction] Remix also has some built-in optimizations for client-side navigation.
[src:remix/introduction] It knows which layouts will persist between the two URLs, so it only fetches the data for the ones that are changing.
[src:remix/introduction] A full document request would require all data to be fetched on the server, wasting resources on your back end and slowing down your app.
[src:remix/introduction] This approach also has UX benefits like not resetting the scroll position of a sidebar nav and allowing you to move focus to something that makes more sense than the top of the document.
[src:remix/introduction] Remix can also prefetch all resources for a page when the user is about to click a link.
[src:remix/introduction] The browser framework knows about the compiler's asset manifest.
[src:remix/introduction] It can match the URL of the link, read the manifest, and then prefetch all data, JavaScript modules, and even CSS resources for the next page.
[src:remix/introduction] This is how Remix apps feel fast even when networks are slow.
[src:remix/introduction] Remix then provides client side APIs, so you can create rich user experiences without changing the fundamental model of HTML and browsers.
[src:remix/introduction] What's most interesting about this code sample is that it is **only additive**.
[src:remix/introduction] The entire interaction is still fundamentally the same thing and even works at a basic level before JavaScript loads, the only difference is the user feedback will be provided by the browser (spinning favicon, etc.) instead of the app (`useNavigation().state`).
[src:remix/introduction] Because Remix reaches into the controller level of the backend, it can do this seamlessly.
[src:remix/introduction] And while it doesn't reach as far back into the stack as server-side frameworks like Rails and Laravel, it does reach way farther up the stack into the browser to make the transition from the back end to the front end seamless.
[src:remix/introduction] Building a plain HTML form and server-side handler in a back-end heavy web framework is just as easy to do as it is in Remix.
[src:remix/introduction] But as soon as you want to cross over into an experience with animated validation messages, focus management, and pending UI, it requires a fundamental change in the code.
[src:remix/introduction] Typically, people build an API route and then bring in a splash of client-side JavaScript to connect the two.
[src:remix/introduction] With Remix, you simply add some code around the existing "server side view" without changing how it works fundamentally.
[src:remix/introduction] The browser runtime takes over the server communication to provide an enhanced user experience beyond the default browser behaviors.
[src:remix/introduction] We borrowed an old term and called this Progressive Enhancement in Remix.
[src:remix/introduction] Start small with a plain HTML form (Remix scales down) and then scale the UI up when you have the time and ambition.
[src:remix/progressive-web-apps] These kinds of apps enjoy all the best parts of the Web — such as discoverability via search engines, being linkable via URLs, and working across multiple form factors, but are progressively enhanced with modern APIs (such as Service Workers and Push).
[src:remix/progressive-web-apps] These features include being installable, working offline, and syncing with and re-engaging the user from the server.
[src:remix/react-software] React can be used to develop single-page, mobile, or server-rendered applications with frameworks like Next.js and React Router.
[src:remix/react-software] Because React is only concerned with the user interface and rendering components to the DOM, React applications often rely on libraries for routing and other client-side functionality.
[src:remix/react-software] A key advantage of React is that it only re-renders those parts of the page that have changed, avoiding unnecessary re-rendering of unchanged DOM elements.
[src:remix/react-software] React is used by an estimated 6% of all websites.
[src:remix/react-software] React adheres to the declarative programming paradigm.
[src:remix/react-software] Developers design views for each state of an application, and React updates and renders components when data changes.
[src:remix/react-software] This is in contrast with imperative programming.
[src:remix/react-software] React code is made of entities called components.
[src:remix/react-software] These components are modular and can be reused.
[src:remix/react-software] React applications typically consist of many layers of components.
[src:remix/react-software] The components are rendered to a root element in the DOM using the React DOM library.
[src:remix/react-software] The two primary ways of declaring components in React are through function components and class components.
[src:remix/react-software] Since React v16.8, using function components is the recommended way.
[src:remix/react-software] Function components, announced at React Conf 2018, and available since React v16.8, are declared with a function that accepts a single "props" argument and returns JSX (JavaScript XML).
[src:remix/react-software] Function components can use internal state with the `useState` Hook.
[src:remix/react-software] On February 16, 2019, React 16.8 was released to the public, introducing React Hooks.
[src:remix/react-software] Hooks are functions that let developers "hook into" React state and lifecycle features from function components.
[src:remix/react-software] Notably, Hooks do not work inside classes — they let developers use more features of React without classes.
[src:remix/react-software] React provides several built-in hooks such as `useState`, `useContext`, `useReducer`, `useMemo` and `useEffect`.
[src:remix/react-software] Others are documented in the Hooks API Reference.
[src:remix/react-software] `useState` and `useEffect`, which are the most commonly used, are for controlling state and side effects, respectively.
[src:remix/react-software] "Only call hooks from React functions" — do not call hooks from plain JavaScript functions so that stateful logic stays with the component.
[src:remix/react-software] Although these rules cannot be enforced at runtime, code analysis tools such as linters can be configured to detect many mistakes during development.
[src:remix/react-software] The rules apply to both usage of Hooks and the implementation of custom Hooks, which may call other Hooks.
[src:remix/react-software] Though a similar concept to Server Side Rendering, RSCs do not send corresponding JavaScript to the client as no hydration occurs.
[src:remix/react-software] As a result, they have no access to hooks.
[src:remix/react-software] Class components are declared using ES6 classes.
[src:remix/react-software] They behave the same way that function components do, but instead of using Hooks to manage state and lifecycle events, they use the lifecycle methods on the `React.Component` base class.
[src:remix/react-software] React itself does not come with built-in support for routing.
[src:remix/react-software] React is primarily a library for building user interfaces, and it does not include a full-fledged routing solution out of the box.
[src:remix/react-software] Third-party libraries can be used to handle routing in React applications, such as React Router.
[src:remix/react-software] It allows the developer to define routes, manage navigation, and handle URL changes in a React-friendly way.
[src:remix/react-software] Another notable feature is the use of a virtual Document Object Model, or Virtual DOM.
[src:remix/react-software] React creates an in-memory data-structure, similar to the browser DOM.
[src:remix/react-software] Every time components are rendered, the result is compared with the virtual DOM.
[src:remix/react-software] It then updates the browser's displayed DOM efficiently with only the computed differences.
[src:remix/react-software] This process is called **reconciliation**.
[src:remix/react-software] This allows the programmer to write code as if the entire page is rendered on each change, while React only renders the components that actually change.
[src:remix/react-software] This selective rendering provides a major performance boost.
[src:remix/react-software] When `ReactDOM.render` is called again for the same component and target, React represents the new UI state in the Virtual DOM and determines which parts (if any) of the living DOM needs to change.
[src:remix/react-software] Lifecycle methods for class-based components use a form of hooking that allows the execution of code at set points during a component's lifetime.
[src:remix/react-software] JSX, or JavaScript XML, is an extension to the JavaScript language syntax.
[src:remix/react-software] Similar in appearance to HTML, JSX provides a way to structure component rendering using syntax familiar to many developers.
[src:remix/react-software] React components are typically written using JSX, although they do not have to be (components may also be written in pure JavaScript).
[src:remix/react-software] During compilation, JSX is converted to JavaScript code.
[src:remix/react-software] JSX is similar to another extension syntax created by Facebook for PHP called XHP.
[src:remix/react-software] The basic architecture of React applies beyond rendering HTML in the browser.
[src:remix/react-software] For example, Facebook has dynamic charts that render to `<canvas>` tags, and Netflix and PayPal use universal loading to render identical HTML on both the server and client.
[src:remix/react-software] React can also be used to develop native apps for Android and iOS using React Native.
[src:remix/react-software] Server-side rendering (SSR) refers to the process of rendering a client-side JavaScript application on the server, rather than in the browser.
[src:remix/react-software] This can improve the performance of the application, especially for users on slower connections or devices.
[src:remix/react-software] With SSR, the initial HTML that is sent to the client includes the fully rendered UI of the application.
[src:remix/react-software] This allows the client's browser to display the UI immediately, rather than having to wait for the JavaScript to download and execute before rendering the UI.
[src:remix/react-software] React supports SSR, which allows developers to render React components on the server and send the resulting HTML to the client.
[src:remix/react-software] This can be useful for improving the performance of the application, as well as for search engine optimization purposes.
[src:remix/react-software] React does not attempt to provide a complete application library.
[src:remix/react-software] It is designed specifically for building user interfaces and therefore does not include many of the tools some developers might consider necessary to build an application.
[src:remix/react-software] This allows the choice of whichever libraries the developer prefers to accomplish tasks such as performing network access or local data storage.
[src:remix/react-software] Common patterns of usage have emerged as the library matures.
[src:remix/react-software] To support React's concept of unidirectional data flow (which might be contrasted with AngularJS's bidirectional flow), the *Flux* architecture was developed as an alternative to the popular model–view–controller architecture.
[src:remix/react-software] Flux features *actions* which are sent through a central *dispatcher* to a *store*, and changes to the store are propagated back to the view.
[src:remix/react-software] When used with React, this propagation is accomplished through component properties.
[src:remix/react-software] Since its conception, Flux has been superseded by libraries such as Redux and MobX.
[src:remix/react-software] Flux can be considered a variant of the observer pattern.
[src:remix/react-software] A React component under the Flux architecture should not directly modify any props passed to it, but should be passed callback functions that create *actions* which are sent by the dispatcher to modify the store.
[src:remix/react-software] The action is an object whose responsibility is to describe what has taken place: for example, an action describing one user "following" another might contain a user id, a target user id, and the type `USER_FOLLOWED_ANOTHER_USER`.
[src:remix/react-software] The stores, which can be thought of as models, can alter themselves in response to actions received from the dispatcher.
[src:remix/react-software] This pattern is sometimes expressed as "properties flow down, actions flow up".
[src:remix/react-software] Many implementations of Flux have been created since its inception, perhaps the most well-known being Redux, which features a single store, often called a single source of truth.
[src:remix/react-software] In February 2019, `useReducer` was introduced as a React hook in the 16.8 release.
[src:remix/react-software] It provides an API that is consistent with Redux, enabling developers to create Redux-like stores that are local to component states.
[src:remix/react-software] React was created by Jordan Walke, a software engineer at Facebook, Inc.
[src:remix/react-software] (now Meta), who initially developed a prototype called "F-Bolt" before later renaming it to "FaxJS".
[src:remix/react-software] This early version is documented in Jordan Walke's GitHub repository.[1] Influences for the project included XHP, an HTML component library for PHP.
[src:remix/react-software] React was first deployed on Facebook's News Feed in 2011 and subsequently integrated into Instagram in 2012.
[src:remix/react-software] React Native, which enables native Android, iOS, and UWP development with React, was announced at Facebook's React Conf in February 2015 and open-sourced in March 2015.
[src:remix/react-software] On April 18, 2017, Facebook announced React Fiber, a new set of internal algorithms for rendering, as opposed to React's old rendering algorithm, Stack.
[src:remix/react-software] React Fiber was to become the foundation of any future improvements and feature development of the React library.
[src:remix/react-software] The actual syntax for programming with React does not change; only the way that the syntax is executed has changed.
[src:remix/react-software] React's old rendering system, Stack, was developed at a time when the focus of the system on dynamic change was not understood.
[src:remix/react-software] Stack was slow to draw complex animation, for example, trying to accomplish all of it in one chunk.
[src:remix/react-software] Fiber breaks down animation into segments that can be spread out over multiple frames.
[src:remix/react-software] Likewise, the structure of a page can be broken into segments that may be maintained and updated separately.
[src:remix/react-software] JavaScript functions and virtual DOM objects are called "fibers", and each can be operated and updated separately, allowing for smoother on-screen rendering.
[src:remix/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0 was released to the public.
[src:remix/react-software] React 16.0 introduced error boundaries, a new component type that catches JavaScript errors anywhere in its child tree and renders a fallback UI instead of crashing the app.
[src:remix/react-software] On October 20, 2020, the React team released React v17.0, notable as the first major release without major changes to the React developer-facing API.
[src:remix/react-software] On March 29, 2022, React 18 was released which introduced a new concurrent renderer, automatic batching and support for server side rendering with Suspense.
[src:remix/react-software] React 18 dropped support for Internet Explorer 11.
[src:remix/react-software] On December 5, 2024, React 19 was released.
[src:remix/react-software] This release introduced Actions, which simplify the process of making state updates using asynchronous functions rather than having to manually handle pending states, errors and optimistic updates.
[src:remix/react-software] React 19 also included support for server components and improved static site generation.
[src:remix/react-software] In October 2025, Meta announced that it would donate React, React Native, and JSX (JavaScript XML) to a new React Foundation, part of the Linux Foundation.
[src:remix/react-software] On 24 February 2026, The React Foundation officially launched with Meta Platforms, Inc. contributing the React project to the Foundation.
[src:remix/react-software] On 29 November 2025, a vulnerability CVE-2025-55182, also known as React2Shell was reported that allowed remote code execution.
[src:remix/react-software] It was assigned a CVSS highest score of 10.0.
[src:remix/react-software] On December 11, 2025, the React team disclosed additional vulnerabilities in React Server Components: denial-of-service issues (CVE-2025-55184 and CVE-2025-67779, CVSS 7.5) and a source code exposure issue (CVE-2025-55183, CVSS 5.3).
[src:remix/react-software] The initial public release of React in May 2013 used the Apache License 2.0.
[src:remix/react-software] Many expressed concerns that Facebook could unfairly exploit the termination clause or that integrating React into a product might complicate a startup company's future acquisition.
[src:remix/react-software] In August 2017, Facebook dismissed the Apache Foundation's downstream concerns and refused to reconsider their license.
[src:remix/react-software] The following month, WordPress decided to switch its Gutenberg and Calypso projects away from React.
[src:remix/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0.0 was released with the MIT license.
[src:remix/react-software] The MIT license change has also been backported to the 15.x release line with React 15.6.2.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:remix/server-side-rendering] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] The latest version of Remix is now React Router v7.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] If you want to use the latest features, you should use the React Router docs to get started.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] This guide will get you familiar with the basic plumbing required to run a Remix app as quickly as possible.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] While there are many starter templates with different runtimes, deploy targets, and databases, we're going to create a bare-bones project from scratch.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] However, this guide will explain everything the CLI does to set up your project, and instead of using the CLI, you can follow these steps.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] If you're just getting started with Remix, we recommend following this guide to understand all the different pieces that make up a Remix app.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Since Remix uses Vite, you'll need to provide a Vite config with the Remix Vite plugin.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] `app/root.jsx` is what we call the "Root Route".
[src:remix/start-quickstart] It's the root layout of your entire app.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] First you will need to specify the type as `module` in `package.json` to satisfy esmodule requirements for `remix-run` and future versions of `vite`.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] You should now see a `build` folder containing a `server` folder (the server version of your app) and a `client` folder (the browser version) with some build artifacts in them.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] You should be able to open up http://localhost:3000 and see the "hello world" page.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] The `build/server` directory created by `remix vite:build` is just a module that you run inside a server like Express, Cloudflare Workers, Netlify, Vercel, Fastly, AWS, Deno, Azure, Fastify, Firebase, ... anywhere.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] If you don't care to set up your own server, you can use `remix-serve`.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] It's a simple express-based server maintained by the Remix team.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] However, Remix is specifically designed to run in *any* JavaScript environment so that you own your stack.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] It is expected many —if not most— production apps will have their own server.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] You can read more about this in Runtimes, Adapters, and Stacks.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Just for kicks, let's stop using `remix-serve` and use express instead.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Now that you own your server, you can debug your app with whatever tooling your server has.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Instead of stopping, rebuilding, and starting your server all the time, you can run Remix in development using Vite in middleware mode.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] This enables instant feedback to changes in your app with React Refresh (Hot Module Replacement) and Remix Hot Data Revalidation.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Vite middleware is not applied if `process.env.NODE_ENV` is set to `"production"`, in which case you'll still be running the regular build output as you did earlier.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Now you can work on your app with immediate feedback.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Give it a try, change the text in `root.jsx` and watch!
[src:remix/start-quickstart] There are default magic files Remix is using that most apps don't need to mess with, but if you want to customize Remix's entry points to the server and browser you can run `remix reveal` and they'll get dumped into your project.
[src:remix/start-quickstart] Congrats, you can add Remix to your resume!
[src:remix/start-quickstart] A few minutes of boilerplate but now you own your stack.
[src:remix/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:remix/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:remix/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:remix/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:remix/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:remix/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:remix/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:remix/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:remix/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:remix/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:remix/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:remix/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:remix/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:remix/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:remix/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:remix/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:remix/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:remix/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:remix/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:remix/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:remix/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:remix/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:remix/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:remix/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:remix/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:remix/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:remix/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:remix/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:remix/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:remix/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:remix/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:remix/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:remix/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:remix/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:remix/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:remix/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:remix/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:remix/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:remix/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:remix/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:remix/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:remix/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:remix/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:remix/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:remix/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:remix/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:remix/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:remix/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:remix/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:remix/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:remix/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:remix/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:remix/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:remix/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:remix/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:remix/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:remix/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:remix/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:remix/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:remix/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:remix/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:remix/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:remix/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:remix/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:remix/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:remix/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:remix/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:remix/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:remix/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:remix/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:remix/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:remix/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:remix/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:remix/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:remix/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:remix/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:remix/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:remix/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:remix/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:remix/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:remix/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:remix/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:remix/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
